  "topic_name": "Refraction of Light",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Light travels in straight lines at a speed of approximately 3 × 10⁸ m/s in vacuum. When light passes from one medium to another, it changes speed and may bend. This bending of light is called refraction. Light bends towards the normal when entering a denser medium (slows down) and away from the normal when entering a rarer medium (speeds up). The refractive index is the ratio of the speed of light in vacuum to the speed in a medium. When light passes through a glass slab, it undergoes lateral displacement. Atmospheric refraction causes phenomena like twinkling of stars, early sunrise/late sunset, and mirages.",
    "rules": [
      "Speed of light in vacuum = 3 × 10⁸ m/s",
      "Light slows down in denser media.",
      "Refraction is the bending of light when passing between media.",
      "Light bends towards normal when entering a denser medium.",
      "Light bends away from normal when entering a rarer medium.",
      "Refractive index = Speed of light in vacuum / Speed in medium",
      "A glass slab causes lateral displacement without changing direction.",
      "Atmospheric refraction causes twinkling of stars.",
      "Mirages are caused by refraction in layers of air."
    ]
  },
